# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kubernetes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Kubernetes is a portable, extensible, open source platform for managing containerized workloads and services that facilitate both declarative configuration and automation.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] It has a large, rapidly growing ecosystem.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Kubernetes services, support, and tools are widely available.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] The name Kubernetes originates from Greek, meaning helmsman or pilot.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] K8s as an abbreviation results from counting the eight letters between the "K" and the "s".
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Google open sourced the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Kubernetes combines over 15 years of Google's experience running production workloads at scale with best-of-breed ideas and practices from the community.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Containers are a good way to bundle and run your applications.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] In a production environment, you need to manage the containers that run the applications and ensure that there is no downtime.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] For example, if a container goes down, another container needs to start.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Wouldn't it be easier if this behavior was handled by a system?
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] That's how Kubernetes comes to the rescue!
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Kubernetes provides you with a framework to run distributed systems resiliently.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] It takes care of scaling and failover for your application, provides deployment patterns, and more.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] For example: Kubernetes can easily manage a canary deployment for your system.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Kubernetes is not a traditional, all-inclusive PaaS (Platform as a Service) system.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Since Kubernetes operates at the container level rather than at the hardware level, it provides some generally applicable features common to PaaS offerings, such as deployment, scaling, load balancing, and lets users integrate their logging, monitoring, and alerting solutions.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] However, Kubernetes is not monolithic, and these default solutions are optional and pluggable.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Kubernetes provides the building blocks for building developer platforms, but preserves user choice and flexibility where it is important.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Let's take a look at why Kubernetes is so useful by going back in time.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Early on, organizations ran applications on physical servers.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] There was no way to define resource boundaries for applications in a physical server, and this caused resource allocation issues.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] For example, if multiple applications run on a physical server, there can be instances where one application would take up most of the resources, and as a result, the other applications would underperform.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] A solution for this would be to run each application on a different physical server.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] But this did not scale as resources were underutilized, and it was expensive for organizations to maintain many physical servers.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] As a solution, virtualization was introduced.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] It allows you to run multiple Virtual Machines (VMs) on a single physical server's CPU.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Virtualization allows applications to be isolated between VMs and provides a level of security as the information of one application cannot be freely accessed by another application.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Virtualization allows better utilization of resources in a physical server and allows better scalability because an application can be added or updated easily, reduces hardware costs, and much more.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] With virtualization you can present a set of physical resources as a cluster of disposable virtual machines.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Each VM is a full machine running all the components, including its own operating system, on top of the virtualized hardware.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Containers are similar to VMs, but they have relaxed isolation properties to share the Operating System (OS) among the applications.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Therefore, containers are considered lightweight.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] Similar to a VM, a container has its own filesystem, share of CPU, memory, process space, and more.
[src:kubernetes/concepts-overview] As they are decoupled from the underlying infrastructure, they are portable across clouds and OS distributions.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] A ConfigMap is an API object used to store non-confidential data in key-value pairs.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Pods can consume ConfigMaps as environment variables, command-line arguments, or as configuration files in a volume.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] A ConfigMap allows you to decouple environment-specific configuration from your container images, so that your applications are easily portable.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] ConfigMap does not provide secrecy or encryption.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] rather than a ConfigMap, or use additional (third party) tools to keep your data private.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Use a ConfigMap for setting configuration data separately from application code.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] For example, imagine that you are developing an application that you can run on your own computer (for development) and in the cloud (to handle real traffic).
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] You write the code to look in an environment variable named `DATABASE_HOST`.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Locally, you set that variable to `localhost`.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] In the cloud, you set it to refer to a Kubernetes Service that exposes the database component to your cluster.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] This lets you fetch a container image running in the cloud and debug the exact same code locally if needed.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] A ConfigMap is not designed to hold large chunks of data.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The data stored in a ConfigMap cannot exceed 1 MiB.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] If you need to store settings that are larger than this limit, you may want to consider mounting a volume or use a separate database or file service.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] A ConfigMap is an API object that lets you store configuration for other objects to use.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Unlike most Kubernetes objects that have a `spec`, a ConfigMap has `data` and `binaryData` fields.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] These fields accept key-value pairs as their values.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Both the `data` field and the `binaryData` are optional.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The `data` field is designed to contain UTF-8 strings while the `binaryData` field is designed to contain binary data as base64-encoded strings.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The name of a ConfigMap must be a valid DNS subdomain name.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Each key under the `data` or the `binaryData` field must consist of alphanumeric characters, `-`, `_` or `.`.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The keys stored in `data` must not overlap with the keys in the `binaryData` field.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Starting from v1.19, you can add an `immutable` field to a ConfigMap definition to create an immutable ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] You can write a Pod `spec` that refers to a ConfigMap and configures the container(s) in that Pod based on the data in the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The Pod and the ConfigMap must be in the same namespace.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] cannot refer to a ConfigMap or any other API objects.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Here's an example ConfigMap that has some keys with single values, and other keys where the value looks like a fragment of a configuration format.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] These different methods lend themselves to different ways of modeling the data being consumed.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] For the first three methods, the kubelet uses the data from the ConfigMap when it launches container(s) for a Pod.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The fourth method means you have to write code to read the ConfigMap and its data.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] However, because you're using the Kubernetes API directly, your application can subscribe to get updates whenever the ConfigMap changes, and react when that happens.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] By accessing the Kubernetes API directly, this technique also lets you access a ConfigMap in a different namespace.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] A ConfigMap doesn't differentiate between single line property values and multi-line file-like values.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] What matters is how Pods and other objects consume those values.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] For this example, defining a volume and mounting it inside the `demo` container as `/config` creates two files, `/config/game.properties` and `/config/user-interface.properties`, even though there are four keys in the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] This is because the Pod definition specifies an `items` array in the `volumes` section.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] If you omit the `items` array entirely, every key in the ConfigMap becomes a file with the same name as the key, and you get 4 files.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] ConfigMaps can be mounted as data volumes.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] ConfigMaps can also be used by other parts of the system, without being directly exposed to the Pod.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] For example, ConfigMaps can hold data that other parts of the system should use for configuration.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The most common way to use ConfigMaps is to configure settings for containers running in a Pod in the same namespace.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] You can also use a ConfigMap separately.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] For example, you might encounter addons or operators that adjust their behavior based on a ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Modify your Pod definition to add a volume under `.spec.volumes[]`.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Name the volume anything, and have a `.spec.volumes[].configMap.name` field set to reference your ConfigMap object.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Add a `.spec.containers[].volumeMounts[]` to each container that needs the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Specify `.spec.containers[].volumeMounts[].readOnly = true` and `.spec.containers[].volumeMounts[].mountPath` to an unused directory name where you would like the ConfigMap to appear.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Modify your image or command line so that the program looks for files in that directory.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Each key in the ConfigMap `data` map becomes the filename under `mountPath`.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Each ConfigMap you want to use needs to be referred to in `.spec.volumes`.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] If there are multiple containers in the Pod, then each container needs its own `volumeMounts` block, but only one `.spec.volumes` is needed per ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] When a ConfigMap currently consumed in a volume is updated, projected keys are eventually updated as well.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The kubelet checks whether the mounted ConfigMap is fresh on every periodic sync.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] However, the kubelet uses its local cache for getting the current value of the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The type of the cache is configurable using the `configMapAndSecretChangeDetectionStrategy` field in the KubeletConfiguration struct.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] A ConfigMap can be either propagated by watch (default), ttl-based, or by redirecting all requests directly to the API server.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] ConfigMaps consumed as environment variables are not updated automatically and require a pod restart.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] volume mount will not receive ConfigMap updates.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Modify your image and/or command line so that the program looks for values in the specified environment variables.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The `envFrom` field instructs Kubernetes to create environment variables from the sources nested within it.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The inner `configMapRef` refers to a ConfigMap by its name and selects all its key-value pairs.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Add the Pod to your cluster, then retrieve its logs to see the output from the printenv command.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Sometimes a Pod won't require access to all the values in a ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] For example, you could have another Pod which only uses the username value from the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] For this use case, you can use the `env.valueFrom` syntax instead, which lets you select individual keys in a ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The name of the environment variable can also be different from the key within the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] In the Pod created from this manifest, you will see that the environment variable `CONFIGMAP_USERNAME` is set to the value of the `username` value from the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Other keys from the ConfigMap data are not copied into the environment.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] It's important to note that the range of characters allowed for environment variable names in pods is restricted.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] If any keys do not meet the rules, those keys are not made available to your container, though the Pod is allowed to start.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] The Kubernetes feature *Immutable Secrets and ConfigMaps* provides an option to set individual Secrets and ConfigMaps as immutable.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] You can create an immutable ConfigMap by setting the `immutable` field to `true`.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Once a ConfigMap is marked as immutable, it is *not* possible to revert this change nor to mutate the contents of the `data` or the `binaryData` field.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] You can only delete and recreate the ConfigMap.
[src:kubernetes/configuration-configmap] Because existing Pods maintain a mount point to the deleted ConfigMap, it is recommended to recreate these pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment manages a set of Pods to run an application workload, usually one that doesn't maintain state.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] A *Deployment* provides declarative updates for Pods and ReplicaSets.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You describe a *desired state* in a Deployment, and the Deployment Controller changes the actual state to the desired state at a controlled rate.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can define Deployments to create new ReplicaSets, or to remove existing Deployments and adopt all their resources with new Deployments.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Do not manage ReplicaSets owned by a Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Consider opening an issue in the main Kubernetes repository if your use case is not covered below.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The following is an example of a Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Before you begin, make sure your Kubernetes cluster is up and running.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Waiting for rollout to finish: 2 out of 3 new replicas have been updated...
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Run the `kubectl get deployments` again a few seconds later.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to this:Notice that the Deployment has created all three replicas, and all replicas are up-to-date (they contain the latest Pod template) and available.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] To see the ReplicaSet (`rs`) created by the Deployment, run `kubectl get rs`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to this:ReplicaSet output shows the following fields:Notice that the name of the ReplicaSet is always formatted as `[DEPLOYMENT-NAME]-[HASH]`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] This name will become the basis for the Pods which are created.The `HASH` string is the same as the `pod-template-hash` label on the ReplicaSet.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] To see the labels automatically generated for each Pod, run `kubectl get pods --show-labels`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to:The created ReplicaSet ensures that there are three `nginx` Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You must specify an appropriate selector and Pod template labels in a Deployment (in this case, `app: nginx`).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Do not overlap labels or selectors with other controllers (including other Deployments and StatefulSets).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Kubernetes doesn't stop you from overlapping, and if multiple controllers have overlapping selectors those controllers might conflict and behave unexpectedly.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The `pod-template-hash` label is added by the Deployment controller to every ReplicaSet that a Deployment creates or adopts.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] This label ensures that child ReplicaSets of a Deployment do not overlap.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] It is generated by hashing the `PodTemplate` of the ReplicaSet and using the resulting hash as the label value that is added to the ReplicaSet selector, Pod template labels, and in any existing Pods that the ReplicaSet might have.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] ) is changed, for example if the labels or container images of the template are updated.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Other updates, such as scaling the Deployment, do not trigger a rollout.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Each time a new Deployment is observed by the Deployment controller, a ReplicaSet is created to bring up the desired Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If the Deployment is updated, the existing ReplicaSet that controls Pods whose labels match `.spec.selector` but whose template does not match `.spec.template` is scaled down.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Eventually, the new ReplicaSet is scaled to `.spec.replicas` and all old ReplicaSets is scaled to 0.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If you update a Deployment while an existing rollout is in progress, the Deployment creates a new ReplicaSet as per the update and start scaling that up, and rolls over the ReplicaSet that it was scaling up previously -- it will add it to its list of old ReplicaSets and start scaling it down.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, suppose you create a Deployment to create 5 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2`, but then update the Deployment to create 5 replicas of `nginx:1.16.1`, when only 3 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2` had been created.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] In that case, the Deployment immediately starts killing the 3 `nginx:1.14.2` Pods that it had created, and starts creating `nginx:1.16.1` Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] It does not wait for the 5 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2` to be created before changing course.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] It is generally discouraged to make label selector updates and it is suggested to plan your selectors up front.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment's label selector is **immutable** after creation; it cannot be updated via `kubectl patch`, `kubectl edit`, `kubectl apply`, or tools like `helm upgrade`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If you must change the selector, you have to delete the Deployment and recreate it.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] By default, deleting the Deployment also deletes its running Pods, causing downtime; use `--cascade=orphan` if you need those Pods to keep running while you recreate the Deployment (see the implications below).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Sometimes, you may want to rollback a Deployment; for example, when the Deployment is not stable, such as crash looping.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] By default, all of the Deployment's rollout history is kept in the system so that you can rollback anytime you want (you can change that by modifying revision history limit).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment's revision is created when a Deployment's rollout is triggered.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] ) is changed, for example if you update the labels or container images of the template.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Other updates, such as scaling the Deployment, do not create a Deployment revision, so that you can facilitate simultaneous manual- or auto-scaling.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] This means that when you roll back to an earlier revision, only the Deployment's Pod template part is rolled back.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Waiting for rollout to finish: 1 out of 3 new replicas have been updated...
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Follow the steps given below to rollback the Deployment from the current version to the previous version, which is version 2.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Assuming horizontal Pod autoscaling is enabled in your cluster, you can set up an autoscaler for your Deployment and choose the minimum and maximum number of Pods you want to run based on the CPU utilization of your existing Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] RollingUpdate Deployments support running multiple versions of an application at the same time.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] When you or an autoscaler scales a RollingUpdate Deployment that is in the middle of a rollout (either in progress or paused), the Deployment controller balances the additional replicas in the existing active ReplicaSets (ReplicaSets with Pods) in order to mitigate risk.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, you are running a Deployment with 10 replicas, maxSurge=3, and maxUnavailable=2.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] In our example above, 3 replicas are added to the old ReplicaSet and 2 replicas are added to the new ReplicaSet.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The rollout process should eventually move all replicas to the new ReplicaSet, assuming the new replicas become healthy.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The rollout status confirms how the replicas were added to each ReplicaSet.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] When you update a Deployment, or plan to, you can pause rollouts for that Deployment before you trigger one or more updates.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] When you're ready to apply those changes, you resume rollouts for the Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] This approach allows you to apply multiple fixes in between pausing and resuming without triggering unnecessary rollouts.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You cannot rollback a paused Deployment until you resume it.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment enters various states during its lifecycle.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] It can be progressing while rolling out a new ReplicaSet, it can be complete, or it can fail to progress.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can monitor the progress for a Deployment by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] This `Progressing` condition will retain a status value of `"True"` until a new rollout is initiated.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The condition holds even when availability of replicas changes (which does instead affect the `Available` condition).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can check if a Deployment has completed by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If the rollout completed successfully, `kubectl rollout status` returns a zero exit code.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Your Deployment may get stuck trying to deploy its newest ReplicaSet without ever completing.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] One way you can detect this condition is to specify a deadline parameter in your Deployment spec: (`.spec.progressDeadlineSeconds`).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] `.spec.progressDeadlineSeconds` denotes the number of seconds the Deployment controller waits before indicating (in the Deployment status) that the Deployment progress has stalled.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] This condition can also fail early and is then set to status value of `"False"` due to reasons as `ReplicaSetCreateError`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Also, the deadline is not taken into account anymore once the Deployment rollout completes.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] See the Kubernetes API conventions for more information on status conditions.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Higher level orchestrators can take advantage of it and act accordingly, for example, rollback the Deployment to its previous version.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If you pause a Deployment rollout, Kubernetes does not check progress against your specified deadline.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can safely pause a Deployment rollout in the middle of a rollout and resume without triggering the condition for exceeding the deadline.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You may experience transient errors with your Deployments, either due to a low timeout that you have set or due to any other kind of error that can be treated as transient.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, let's suppose you have insufficient quota.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can address an issue of insufficient quota by scaling down your Deployment, by scaling down other controllers you may be running, or by increasing quota in your namespace.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If you satisfy the quota conditions and the Deployment controller then completes the Deployment rollout, you'll see the Deployment's status update with a successful condition (`status: "True"` and `reason: NewReplicaSetAvailable`).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] `type: Available` with `status: "True"` means that your Deployment has minimum availability.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Minimum availability is dictated by the parameters specified in the deployment strategy.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can check if a Deployment has failed to progress by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] `kubectl rollout status` returns a non-zero exit code if the Deployment has exceeded the progression deadline.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] All actions that apply to a complete Deployment also apply to a failed Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can scale it up/down, roll back to a previous revision, or even pause it if you need to apply multiple tweaks in the Deployment Pod template.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] You can set `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` field in a Deployment to specify how many old ReplicaSets for this Deployment you want to retain.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The rest will be garbage-collected in the background.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Explicitly setting this field to 0, will result in cleaning up all the history of your Deployment thus that Deployment will not be able to roll back.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] The cleanup only starts **after** a Deployment reaches a complete state.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If you set `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` to 0, any rollout nonetheless triggers creation of a new ReplicaSet before Kubernetes removes the old one.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] Even with a non-zero revision history limit, you can have more ReplicaSets than the limit you configure.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, if pods are crash looping, and there are multiple rolling updates events triggered over time, you might end up with more ReplicaSets than the `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` because the Deployment never reaches a complete state.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p01] If you want to roll out releases to a subset of users or servers using the Deployment, you can create multiple Deployments, one for each release, following the canary pattern described in managing resources.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] As with all other Kubernetes configs, a Deployment needs `.apiVersion`, `.kind`, and `.metadata` fields.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] For general information about working with config files, see deploying applications, configuring containers, and using kubectl to manage resources documents.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] When the control plane creates new Pods for a Deployment, the `.metadata.name` of the Deployment is part of the basis for naming those Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The name of a Deployment must be a valid DNS subdomain value, but this can produce unexpected results for the Pod hostnames.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] For best compatibility, the name should follow the more restrictive rules for a DNS label.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment also needs a `.spec` section.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The `.spec.template` and `.spec.selector` are the only required fields of the `.spec`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] It has exactly the same schema as a Pod, except it is nested and does not have an `apiVersion` or `kind`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] In addition to required fields for a Pod, a Pod template in a Deployment must specify appropriate labels and an appropriate restart policy.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] For labels, make sure not to overlap with other controllers.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Only a `.spec.template.spec.restartPolicy` equal to `Always` is allowed, which is the default if not specified.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.replicas` is an optional field that specifies the number of desired Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] If a HorizontalPodAutoscaler (or any similar API for horizontal scaling) is managing scaling for a Deployment, don't set `.spec.replicas`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Instead, allow the Kubernetes control plane to manage the `.spec.replicas` field automatically.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.selector` is a required field that specifies a label selector for the Pods targeted by this Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.selector` must match `.spec.template.metadata.labels`, or it will be rejected by the API.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] In API version `apps/v1`, `.spec.selector` and `.metadata.labels` do not default to `.spec.template.metadata.labels` if not set.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Also note that `.spec.selector` is immutable after creation of the Deployment in `apps/v1`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment may terminate Pods whose labels match the selector if their template is different from `.spec.template` or if the total number of such Pods exceeds `.spec.replicas`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] It brings up new Pods with `.spec.template` if the number of Pods is less than the desired number.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] You should not create other Pods whose labels match this selector, either directly, by creating another Deployment, or by creating another controller such as a ReplicaSet or a ReplicationController.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] If you do so, the first Deployment thinks that it created these other Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Kubernetes does not stop you from doing this.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] If you have multiple controllers that have overlapping selectors, the controllers will fight with each other and won't behave correctly.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy` specifies the strategy used to replace old Pods by new ones.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.type` can be "Recreate" or "RollingUpdate".
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] All existing Pods are killed before new ones are created when `.spec.strategy.type==Recreate`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] This will only guarantee Pod termination previous to creation for upgrades.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] If you upgrade a Deployment, all Pods of the old revision will be terminated immediately.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Successful removal is awaited before any Pod of the new revision is created.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] If you manually delete a Pod, the lifecycle is controlled by the ReplicaSet and the replacement will be created immediately (even if the old Pod is still in a Terminating state).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The Deployment updates Pods in a rolling update fashion (gradually scale down the old ReplicaSets and scale up the new one) when `.spec.strategy.type==RollingUpdate`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] You can specify `maxUnavailable` and `maxSurge` to control the rolling update process.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxUnavailable` is an optional field that specifies the maximum number of Pods that can be unavailable during the update process.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The value can be an absolute number (for example, 5) or a percentage of desired Pods (for example, 10%).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The absolute number is calculated from percentage by rounding down.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The value cannot be 0 if `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxSurge` is 0.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] For example, when this value is set to 30%, the old ReplicaSet can be scaled down to 70% of desired Pods immediately when the rolling update starts.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Once new Pods are ready, old ReplicaSet can be scaled down further, followed by scaling up the new ReplicaSet, ensuring that the total number of Pods available at all times during the update is at least 70% of the desired Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxSurge` is an optional field that specifies the maximum number of Pods that can be created over the desired number of Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The value cannot be 0 if `maxUnavailable` is 0.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The absolute number is calculated from the percentage by rounding up.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] For example, when this value is set to 30%, the new ReplicaSet can be scaled up immediately when the rolling update starts, such that the total number of old and new Pods does not exceed 130% of desired Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Once old Pods have been killed, the new ReplicaSet can be scaled up further, ensuring that the total number of Pods running at any time during the update is at most 130% of desired Pods.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The Deployment controller will keep retrying the Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] If specified, this field needs to be greater than `.spec.minReadySeconds`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.minReadySeconds` is an optional field that specifies the minimum number of seconds for which a newly created Pod should be ready without any of its containers crashing, for it to be considered available.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] This defaults to 0 (the Pod will be considered available as soon as it is ready).
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] To learn more about when a Pod is considered ready, see Container Probes.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Pods that become terminating due to deletion or scale down may take a long time to terminate, and may consume additional resources during that period.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] As a result, the total number of all pods can temporarily exceed `.spec.replicas`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] Terminating pods can be tracked using the `.status.terminatingReplicas` field of the Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment's revision history is stored in the ReplicaSets it controls.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` is an optional field that specifies the number of old ReplicaSets to retain to allow rollback.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] These old ReplicaSets consume resources in `etcd` and crowd the output of `kubectl get rs`.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The configuration of each Deployment revision is stored in its ReplicaSets; therefore, once an old ReplicaSet is deleted, you lose the ability to rollback to that revision of Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] By default, 10 old ReplicaSets will be kept, however its ideal value depends on the frequency and stability of new Deployments.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] More specifically, setting this field to zero means that all old ReplicaSets with 0 replicas will be cleaned up.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] In this case, a new Deployment rollout cannot be undone, since its revision history is cleaned up.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.paused` is an optional boolean field for pausing and resuming a Deployment.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] The only difference between a paused Deployment and one that is not paused, is that any changes into the PodTemplateSpec of the paused Deployment will not trigger new rollouts as long as it is paused.
[src:kubernetes/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment is not paused by default when it is created.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Expose an application running in your cluster behind a single outward-facing endpoint, even when the workload is split across multiple backends.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In Kubernetes, a Service is a method for exposing a network application that is running as one or more Pods in your cluster.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] A key aim of Services in Kubernetes is that you don't need to modify your existing application to use an unfamiliar service discovery mechanism.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can run code in Pods, whether this is a code designed for a cloud-native world, or an older app you've containerized.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You use a Service to make that set of Pods available on the network so that clients can interact with it.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you use a Deployment to run your app, that Deployment can create and destroy Pods dynamically.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] From one moment to the next, you don't know how many of those Pods are working and healthy; you might not even know what those healthy Pods are named.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes Pods are created and destroyed to match the desired state of your cluster.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Pods are ephemeral resources (you should not expect that an individual Pod is reliable and durable).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Each Pod gets its own IP address (Kubernetes expects network plugins to ensure this).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For a given Deployment in your cluster, the set of Pods running in one moment in time could be different from the set of Pods running that application a moment later.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This leads to a problem: if some set of Pods (call them "backends") provides functionality to other Pods (call them "frontends") inside your cluster, how do the frontends find out and keep track of which IP address to connect to, so that the frontend can use the backend part of the workload?
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The Service API, part of Kubernetes, is an abstraction to help you expose groups of Pods over a network.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Each Service object defines a logical set of endpoints (usually these endpoints are Pods) along with a policy about how to make those pods accessible.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For example, consider a stateless image-processing backend which is running with 3 replicas.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Those replicas are fungible—frontends do not care which backend they use.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] While the actual Pods that compose the backend set may change, the frontend clients should not need to be aware of that, nor should they need to keep track of the set of backends themselves.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The Service abstraction enables this decoupling.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The set of Pods targeted by a Service is usually determined by a selector that you define.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] To learn about other ways to define Service endpoints, see Services *without* selectors.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If your workload speaks HTTP, you might choose to use an Ingress to control how web traffic reaches that workload.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Ingress is not a Service type, but it acts as the entry point for your cluster.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] An Ingress lets you consolidate your routing rules into a single resource, so that you can expose multiple components of your workload, running separately in your cluster, behind a single listener.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The Gateway API for Kubernetes provides extra capabilities beyond Ingress and Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can add Gateway to your cluster - it is a family of extension APIs, implemented using CustomResourceDefinitions - and then use these to configure access to network services that are running in your cluster.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you're able to use Kubernetes APIs for service discovery in your application, you can query the API server for matching EndpointSlices.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes updates the EndpointSlices for a Service whenever the set of Pods in a Service changes.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For non-native applications, Kubernetes offers ways to place a network port or load balancer in between your application and the backend Pods.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Either way, your workload can use these service discovery mechanisms to find the target it wants to connect to.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] A Service is an object (the same way that a Pod or a ConfigMap is an object).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can create, view or modify Service definitions using the Kubernetes API.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Usually you use a tool such as `kubectl` to make those API calls for you.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For example, suppose you have a set of Pods that each listen on TCP port 9376 and are labelled as `app.kubernetes.io/name=MyApp`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Applying this manifest creates a new Service named "my-service" with the default ClusterIP service type.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The Service targets TCP port 9376 on any Pod with the `app.kubernetes.io/name: MyApp` label.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes assigns this Service an IP address (the *cluster IP*), that is used by the virtual IP address mechanism.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For more details on that mechanism, read Virtual IPs and Service Proxies.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The controller for that Service continuously scans for Pods that match its selector, and then makes any necessary updates to the set of EndpointSlices for the Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The name of a Service object must be a valid RFC 1123 label name.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Port definitions in Pods have names, and you can reference these names in the `targetPort` attribute of a Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This works even if there is a mixture of Pods in the Service using a single configured name, with the same network protocol available via different port numbers.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This offers a lot of flexibility for deploying and evolving your Services.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For example, you can change the port numbers that Pods expose in the next version of your backend software, without breaking clients.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The default protocol for Services is TCP; you can also use any other supported protocol.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Because many Services need to expose more than one port, Kubernetes supports multiple port definitions for a single Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Each port definition can have the same `protocol`, or a different one.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Services most commonly abstract access to Kubernetes Pods thanks to the selector, but when used with a corresponding set of EndpointSlices objects and without a selector, the Service can abstract other kinds of backends, including ones that run outside the cluster.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In any of these scenarios you can define a Service *without* specifying a selector to match Pods.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Because this Service has no selector, the corresponding EndpointSlice objects are not created automatically.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can map the Service to the network address and port where it's running, by adding an EndpointSlice object manually.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When you create an EndpointSlice object for a Service, you can use any name for the EndpointSlice.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Each EndpointSlice in a namespace must have a unique name.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You link an EndpointSlice to a Service by setting the `kubernetes.io/service-name` label on that EndpointSlice.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The endpoint IP addresses cannot be the cluster IPs of other Kubernetes Services, because kube-proxy doesn't support virtual IPs as a destination.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For an EndpointSlice that you create yourself, or in your own code, you should also pick a value to use for the label `endpointslice.kubernetes.io/managed-by`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you create your own controller code to manage EndpointSlices, consider using a value similar to `"my-domain.example/name-of-controller"`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you are using a third party tool, use the name of the tool in all-lowercase and change spaces and other punctuation to dashes (`-`).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If people are directly using a tool such as `kubectl` to manage EndpointSlices, use a name that describes this manual management, such as `"staff"` or `"cluster-admins"`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You should avoid using the reserved value `"controller"`, which identifies EndpointSlices managed by Kubernetes' own control plane.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Accessing a Service without a selector works the same as if it had a selector.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In the example for a Service without a selector, traffic is routed to one of the two endpoints defined in the EndpointSlice manifest: a TCP connection to 10.1.2.3 or 10.4.5.6, on port 9376.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The Kubernetes API server does not allow proxying to endpoints that are not mapped to pods.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] where the service has no selector will fail due to this constraint.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This prevents the Kubernetes API server from being used as a proxy to endpoints the caller may not be authorized to access.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] An `ExternalName` Service is a special case of Service that does not have selectors and uses DNS names instead.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For more information, see the ExternalName section.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] EndpointSlices are objects that represent a subset (a *slice*) of the backing network endpoints for a Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Your Kubernetes cluster tracks how many endpoints each EndpointSlice represents.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If there are so many endpoints for a Service that a threshold is reached, then Kubernetes adds another empty EndpointSlice and stores new endpoint information there.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] By default, Kubernetes makes a new EndpointSlice once the existing EndpointSlices all contain at least 100 endpoints.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes does not make the new EndpointSlice until an extra endpoint needs to be added.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] See EndpointSlices for more information about this API.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The EndpointSlice API is the evolution of the older Endpoints API.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Because of this, it is recommended that all clients use the EndpointSlice API rather than Endpoints.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes limits the number of endpoints that can fit in a single Endpoints object.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When there are over 1000 backing endpoints for a Service, Kubernetes truncates the data in the Endpoints object.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Because a Service can be linked with more than one EndpointSlice, the 1000 backing endpoint limit only affects the legacy Endpoints API.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In that case, Kubernetes selects at most 1000 possible backend endpoints to store into the Endpoints object, and sets an annotation on the Endpoints: `endpoints.kubernetes.io/over-capacity: truncated`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The control plane also removes that annotation if the number of backend Pods drops below 1000.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Traffic is still sent to backends, but any load balancing mechanism that relies on the legacy Endpoints API only sends traffic to at most 1000 of the available backing endpoints.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The same API limit means that you cannot manually update an Endpoints to have more than 1000 endpoints.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The `appProtocol` field provides a way to specify an application protocol for each Service port.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This is used as a hint for implementations to offer richer behavior for protocols that they understand.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The value of this field is mirrored by the corresponding Endpoints and EndpointSlice objects.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This field follows standard Kubernetes label syntax.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For some Services, you need to expose more than one port.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes lets you configure multiple port definitions on a Service object.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When using multiple ports for a Service, you must give all of your ports names so that these are unambiguous.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] As with Kubernetes names in general, names for ports must only contain lowercase alphanumeric characters and `-`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Port names must also start and end with an alphanumeric character.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For example, the names `123-abc` and `web` are valid, but `123_abc` and `-web` are not.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For some parts of your application (for example, frontends) you may want to expose a Service onto an external IP address, one that's accessible from outside of your cluster.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes Service types allow you to specify what kind of Service you want.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Exposes the Service on a cluster-internal IP.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Choosing this value makes the Service only reachable from within the cluster.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Exposes the Service externally using an external load balancer.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes does not directly offer a load balancing component; you must provide one, or you can integrate your Kubernetes cluster with a cloud provider.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] record with that external hostname value.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The `type` field in the Service API is designed as nested functionality - each level adds to the previous.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] However there is an exception to this nested design.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can define a `LoadBalancer` Service by disabling the load balancer `NodePort` allocation.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This default Service type assigns an IP address from a pool of IP addresses that your cluster has reserved for that purpose.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Several of the other types for Service build on the `ClusterIP` type as a foundation.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you define a Service that has the `.spec.clusterIP` set to `"None"` then Kubernetes does not assign an IP address.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] See headless Services for more information.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can specify your own cluster IP address as part of a `Service` creation request.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] To do this, set the `.spec.clusterIP` field.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For example, if you already have an existing DNS entry that you wish to reuse, or legacy systems that are configured for a specific IP address and difficult to re-configure.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The IP address that you choose must be a valid IPv4 or IPv6 address from within the `service-cluster-ip-range` CIDR range that is configured for the API server.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you try to create a Service with an invalid `clusterIP` address value, the API server will return a 422 HTTP status code to indicate that there's a problem.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Read avoiding collisions to learn how Kubernetes helps reduce the risk and impact of two different Services both trying to use the same IP address.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you set the `type` field to `NodePort`, the Kubernetes control plane allocates a port from a range specified by `--service-node-port-range` flag (default: 30000-32767).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Each node proxies that port (the same port number on every Node) into your Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Your Service reports the allocated port in its `.spec.ports[*].nodePort` field.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Using a NodePort gives you the freedom to set up your own load balancing solution, to configure environments that are not fully supported by Kubernetes, or even to expose one or more nodes' IP addresses directly.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For a node port Service, Kubernetes additionally allocates a port (TCP, UDP or SCTP to match the protocol of the Service).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Every node in the cluster configures itself to listen on that assigned port and to forward traffic to one of the ready endpoints associated with that Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You'll be able to contact the `type: NodePort` Service, from outside the cluster, by connecting to any node using the appropriate protocol (for example: TCP), and the appropriate port (as assigned to that Service).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you want a specific port number, you can specify a value in the `nodePort` field.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The control plane will either allocate you that port or report that the API transaction failed.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This means that you need to take care of possible port collisions yourself.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You also have to use a valid port number, one that's inside the range configured for NodePort use.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The policy for assigning ports to NodePort services applies to both the auto-assignment and the manual assignment scenarios.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When a user wants to create a NodePort service that uses a specific port, the target port may conflict with another port that has already been assigned.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] To avoid this problem, the port range for NodePort services is divided into two bands.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Dynamic port assignment uses the upper band by default, and it may use the lower band once the upper band has been exhausted.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Users can then allocate from the lower band with a lower risk of port collision.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] See Avoid Collisions Assigning Ports to NodePort Services for more details on how the static and dynamic bands are calculated.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can set up nodes in your cluster to use a particular IP address for serving node port services.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You might want to do this if each node is connected to multiple networks (for example: one network for application traffic, and another network for traffic between nodes and the control plane).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you want to specify particular IP address(es) to proxy the port, you can set the `--nodeport-addresses` flag for kube-proxy or the equivalent `nodePortAddresses` field of the kube-proxy configuration file to particular IP block(s).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This flag takes a comma-delimited list of IP blocks (e.g.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] `10.0.0.0/8`, `192.0.2.0/25`) to specify IP address ranges that kube-proxy should consider as local to this node.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For example, if you start kube-proxy with the `--nodeport-addresses=127.0.0.0/8` flag, kube-proxy only selects the loopback interface for NodePort Services.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The default for `--nodeport-addresses` is an empty list.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This means that kube-proxy should consider all available network interfaces for NodePort.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] (That's also compatible with earlier Kubernetes releases.)Note:This Service is visible as `<NodeIP>:spec.ports[*].nodePort` and `.spec.clusterIP:spec.ports[*].port`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If the `--nodeport-addresses` flag for kube-proxy or the equivalent field in the kube-proxy configuration file is set, `<NodeIP>` would be a filtered node IP address (or possibly IP addresses).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] On cloud providers which support external load balancers, setting the `type` field to `LoadBalancer` provisions a load balancer for your Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The actual creation of the load balancer happens asynchronously, and information about the provisioned balancer is published in the Service's `.status.loadBalancer` field.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Traffic from the external load balancer is directed at the backend Pods.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The cloud provider decides how it is load balanced.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] To implement a Service of `type: LoadBalancer`, Kubernetes typically starts off by making the changes that are equivalent to you requesting a Service of `type: NodePort`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The cloud-controller-manager component then configures the external load balancer to forward traffic to that assigned node port.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can configure a load balanced Service to omit assigning a node port, provided that the cloud provider implementation supports this.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Some cloud providers allow you to specify the `loadBalancerIP`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In those cases, the load-balancer is created with the user-specified `loadBalancerIP`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If the `loadBalancerIP` field is not specified, the load balancer is set up with an ephemeral IP address.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you specify a `loadBalancerIP` but your cloud provider does not support the feature, the `loadbalancerIP` field that you set is ignored.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The`.spec.loadBalancerIP` field for a Service was deprecated in Kubernetes v1.24.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This field was under-specified and its meaning varies across implementations.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] It also cannot support dual-stack networking.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This field may be removed in a future API version.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you're integrating with a provider that supports specifying the load balancer IP address(es) for a Service via a (provider specific) annotation, you should switch to doing that.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you are writing code for a load balancer integration with Kubernetes, avoid using this field.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can integrate with Gateway rather than Service, or you can define your own (provider specific) annotations on the Service that specify the equivalent detail.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Load balancer health checks are critical to modern applications.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] They are used to determine which server (virtual machine, or IP address) the load balancer should dispatch traffic to.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The Kubernetes APIs do not define how health checks have to be implemented for Kubernetes managed load balancers, instead it's the cloud providers (and the people implementing integration code) who decide on the behavior.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Load balancer health checks are extensively used within the context of supporting the `externalTrafficPolicy` field for Services.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] By default, for LoadBalancer type of Services, when there is more than one port defined, all ports must have the same protocol, and the protocol must be one which is supported by the cloud provider.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The feature gate `MixedProtocolLBService` (enabled by default for the kube-apiserver as of v1.24) allows the use of different protocols for LoadBalancer type of Services, when there is more than one port defined.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The set of protocols that can be used for load balanced Services is defined by your cloud provider; they may impose restrictions beyond what the Kubernetes API enforces.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can optionally disable node port allocation for a Service of `type: LoadBalancer`, by setting the field `spec.allocateLoadBalancerNodePorts` to `false`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This should only be used for load balancer implementations that route traffic directly to pods as opposed to using node ports.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] By default, `spec.allocateLoadBalancerNodePorts` is `true` and type LoadBalancer Services will continue to allocate node ports.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If `spec.allocateLoadBalancerNodePorts` is set to `false` on an existing Service with allocated node ports, those node ports will **not** be de-allocated automatically.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You must explicitly remove the `nodePorts` entry in every Service port to de-allocate those node ports.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For a Service with `type` set to `LoadBalancer`, the `.spec.loadBalancerClass` field enables you to use a load balancer implementation other than the cloud provider default.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] By default, `.spec.loadBalancerClass` is not set and a `LoadBalancer` type of Service uses the cloud provider's default load balancer implementation if the cluster is configured with a cloud provider using the `--cloud-provider` component flag.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you specify `.spec.loadBalancerClass`, it is assumed that a load balancer implementation that matches the specified class is watching for Services.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Any default load balancer implementation (for example, the one provided by the cloud provider) will ignore Services that have this field set.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] `spec.loadBalancerClass` can be set on a Service of type `LoadBalancer` only.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The value of `spec.loadBalancerClass` must be a label-style identifier, with an optional prefix such as "`internal-vip`" or "`example.com/internal-vip`".
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Unprefixed names are reserved for end-users.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For a Service of `type: LoadBalancer`, a controller can set `.status.loadBalancer.ingress.ipMode`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The `.status.loadBalancer.ingress.ipMode` specifies how the load-balancer IP behaves.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] It may be specified only when the `.status.loadBalancer.ingress.ip` field is also specified.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] There are two possible values for `.status.loadBalancer.ingress.ipMode`: "VIP" and "Proxy".
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The default value is "VIP" meaning that traffic is delivered to the node with the destination set to the load-balancer's IP and port.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Service implementations may use this information to adjust traffic routing.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In a mixed environment it is sometimes necessary to route traffic from Services inside the same (virtual) network address block.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In a split-horizon DNS environment you would need two Services to be able to route both external and internal traffic to your endpoints.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Services of type ExternalName map a Service to a DNS name, not to a typical selector such as `my-service` or `cassandra`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You specify these Services with the `spec.externalName` parameter.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] A Service of `type: ExternalName` accepts an IPv4 address string, but treats that string as a DNS name comprised of digits, not as an IP address (the internet does not however allow such names in DNS).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Services with external names that resemble IPv4 addresses are not resolved by DNS servers.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you want to map a Service directly to a specific IP address, consider using headless Services.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When looking up the host `my-service.prod.svc.cluster.local`, the cluster DNS Service returns a `CNAME` record with the value `my.database.example.com`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Accessing `my-service` works in the same way as other Services but with the crucial difference that redirection happens at the DNS level rather than via proxying or forwarding.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Should you later decide to move your database into your cluster, you can start its Pods, add appropriate selectors or endpoints, and change the Service's `type`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You may have trouble using ExternalName for some common protocols, including HTTP and HTTPS.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you use ExternalName then the hostname used by clients inside your cluster is different from the name that the ExternalName references.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For protocols that use hostnames this difference may lead to errors or unexpected responses.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] HTTP requests will have a `Host:` header that the origin server does not recognize; TLS servers will not be able to provide a certificate matching the hostname that the client connected to.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Sometimes you don't need load-balancing and a single Service IP.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In this case, you can create what are termed *headless Services*, by explicitly specifying `"None"` for the cluster IP address (`.spec.clusterIP`).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can use a headless Service to interface with other service discovery mechanisms, without being tied to Kubernetes' implementation.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For headless Services, a cluster IP is not allocated, kube-proxy does not handle these Services, and there is no load balancing or proxying done by the platform for them.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] A headless Service allows a client to connect to whichever Pod it prefers, directly.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Services that are headless don't configure routes and packet forwarding using virtual IP addresses and proxies; instead, headless Services report the endpoint IP addresses of the individual pods via internal DNS records, served through the cluster's DNS service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] To define a headless Service, you make a Service with `.spec.type` set to ClusterIP (which is also the default for `type`), and you additionally set `.spec.clusterIP` to None.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The string value None is a special case and is not the same as leaving the `.spec.clusterIP` field unset.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For headless Services that define selectors, the endpoints controller creates EndpointSlices in the Kubernetes API, and modifies the DNS configuration to return A or AAAA records (IPv4 or IPv6 addresses) that point directly to the Pods backing the Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For headless Services that do not define selectors, the control plane does not create EndpointSlice objects.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When you define a headless Service without a selector, the `port` must match the `targetPort`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For clients running inside your cluster, Kubernetes supports two primary modes of finding a Service: environment variables and DNS.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When a Pod is run on a Node, the kubelet adds a set of environment variables for each active Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] It adds `{SVCNAME}_SERVICE_HOST` and `{SVCNAME}_SERVICE_PORT` variables, where the Service name is upper-cased and dashes are converted to underscores.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When you have a Pod that needs to access a Service, and you are using the environment variable method to publish the port and cluster IP to the client Pods, you must create the Service *before* the client Pods come into existence.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Otherwise, those client Pods won't have their environment variables populated.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you only use DNS to discover the cluster IP for a Service, you don't need to worry about this ordering issue.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes also supports and provides variables that are compatible with Docker Engine's "*legacy container links*" feature.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can read `makeLinkVariables` to see how this is implemented in Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can (and almost always should) set up a DNS service for your Kubernetes cluster using an add-on.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] A cluster-aware DNS server, such as CoreDNS, watches the Kubernetes API for new Services and creates a set of DNS records for each one.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If DNS has been enabled throughout your cluster then all Pods should automatically be able to resolve Services by their DNS name.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] For example, if you have a Service called `my-service` in a Kubernetes namespace `my-ns`, the control plane and the DNS Service acting together create a DNS record for `my-service.my-ns`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Pods in the `my-ns` namespace should be able to find the service by doing a name lookup for `my-service` (`my-service.my-ns` would also work).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Pods in other namespaces must qualify the name as `my-service.my-ns`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] These names will resolve to the cluster IP assigned for the Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Kubernetes also supports DNS SRV (Service) records for named ports.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If the `my-service.my-ns` Service has a port named `http` with the protocol set to `TCP`, you can do a DNS SRV query for `_http._tcp.my-service.my-ns` to discover the port number for `http`, as well as the IP address.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The Kubernetes DNS server is the only way to access `ExternalName` Services.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can find more information about `ExternalName` resolution in DNS for Services and Pods.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Read Virtual IPs and Service Proxies explains the mechanism Kubernetes provides to expose a Service with a virtual IP address.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can set the `.spec.internalTrafficPolicy` and `.spec.externalTrafficPolicy` fields to control how Kubernetes routes traffic to healthy (“ready”) backends.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] The `.spec.trafficDistribution` field provides another way to influence traffic routing within a Kubernetes Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] While traffic policies focus on strict semantic guarantees, traffic distribution allows you to express *preferences* (such as routing to topologically closer endpoints).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] This can help optimize for performance, cost, or reliability.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Indicates a preference for routing traffic to endpoints that are in the same zone as the client.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Indicates a preference for routing traffic to endpoints that are on the same node as the client.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If the field is not set, the implementation will apply its default routing strategy.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If you want to make sure that connections from a particular client are passed to the same Pod each time, you can configure session affinity based on the client's IP address.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] All users should begin migrating away from `externalIPs`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Consider using an external load balancer controller or a Gateway API implementation instead.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] If there are external IPs that route to one or more cluster nodes, Kubernetes Services can be exposed on those `externalIPs`.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When network traffic arrives into the cluster, with the external IP (as destination IP) and the port matching that Service, rules and routes that Kubernetes has configured ensure that the traffic is routed to one of the endpoints for that Service.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] When you define a Service, you can specify `externalIPs` for any service type.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] In the example below, the Service named `"my-service"` can be accessed by clients using TCP, on `"198.51.100.32:80"` (calculated from `.spec.externalIPs[]` and `.spec.ports[].port`).
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] ; these are the responsibility of the cluster administrator.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] Service is a top-level resource in the Kubernetes REST API.
[src:kubernetes/services-networking-service] You can find more details about the Service API object.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A *Pod* (as in a pod of whales or pea pod) is a group of one or more containers, with shared storage and network resources, and a specification for how to run the containers.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A Pod's contents are always co-located and co-scheduled, and run in a shared context.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A Pod models an application-specific "logical host": it contains one or more application containers which are relatively tightly coupled.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] In non-cloud contexts, applications executed on the same physical or virtual machine are analogous to cloud applications executed on the same logical host.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] As well as application containers, a Pod can contain init containers that run during Pod startup.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] You can also inject ephemeral containers for debugging a running Pod.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] into each node in the cluster so that Pods can run there.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The shared context of a Pod is a set of Linux namespaces, cgroups, and potentially other facets of isolation - the same things that isolate a container.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Within a Pod's context, the individual applications may have further sub-isolations applied.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A Pod is similar to a set of containers with shared namespaces and shared filesystem volumes.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The following is an example of a Pod which consists of a container running the image `nginx:1.14.2`.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Pods are generally not created directly and are created using workload resources.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] See Working with Pods for more information on how Pods are used with workload resources.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Usually you don't need to create Pods directly, even singleton Pods.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Instead, create them using workload resources such as Deployment or Job.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] If your Pods need to track state, consider the StatefulSet resource.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Each Pod is meant to run a single instance of a given application.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] If you want to scale your application horizontally (to provide more overall resources by running more instances), you should use multiple Pods, one for each instance.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] In Kubernetes, this is typically referred to as *replication*.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Replicated Pods are usually created and managed as a group by a workload resource and its controller.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] See Pods and controllers for more information on how Kubernetes uses workload resources, and their controllers, to implement application scaling and auto-healing.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Pods natively provide two kinds of shared resources for their constituent containers: networking and storage.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] You'll rarely create individual Pods directly in Kubernetes—even singleton Pods.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] This is because Pods are designed as relatively ephemeral, disposable entities.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] When a Pod gets created (directly by you, or indirectly by a controller), the new Pod is scheduled to run on a Node in your cluster.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The Pod remains on that node until the Pod finishes execution, the Pod object is deleted, the Pod is *evicted* for lack of resources, or the node fails.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Restarting a container in a Pod should not be confused with restarting a Pod.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A Pod is not a process, but an environment for running container(s).
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The name of a Pod must be a valid DNS subdomain value, but this can produce unexpected results for the Pod hostname.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] You should set the `.spec.os.name` field to either `windows` or `linux` to indicate the OS on which you want the pod to run.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] These two are the only operating systems supported for now by Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] In the future, this list may be expanded.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] In Kubernetes v1.36, the value of `.spec.os.name` does not affect how the kube-scheduler picks a node for the Pod to run on.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] In any cluster where there is more than one operating system for running nodes, you should set the kubernetes.io/os label correctly on each node, and define pods with a `nodeSelector` based on the operating system label.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The kube-scheduler assigns your pod to a node based on other criteria and may or may not succeed in picking a suitable node placement where the node OS is right for the containers in that Pod.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The Pod security standards also use this field to avoid enforcing policies that aren't relevant to the operating system.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] You can use workload resources to create and manage multiple Pods for you.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A controller for the resource handles replication and rollout and automatic healing in case of Pod failure.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] For example, if a Node fails, a controller notices that Pods on that Node have stopped working and creates a replacement Pod.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The scheduler places the replacement Pod onto a healthy Node.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] By default, Kubernetes schedules every Pod individually.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] However, some tightly-coupled applications need a group of Pods to be scheduled simultaneously to function correctly.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] You can link a Pod to a PodGroup using the scheduling group field (`spec.schedulingGroup`).
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] This tells the `kube-scheduler` that the `Pod` belongs to a specific group, enabling it to apply group-level coordinated placement decisions for the entire group at once.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Controllers for workload resources create Pods from a *pod template* and manage those Pods on your behalf.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] PodTemplates are specifications for creating Pods, and are included in workload resources such as Deployments, Jobs, and DaemonSets.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Each controller for a workload resource uses the `PodTemplate` inside the workload object to make actual Pods.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The `PodTemplate` is part of the desired state of whatever workload resource you used to run your app.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] When you create a Pod, you can include environment variables in the Pod template for the containers that run in the Pod.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The sample below is a manifest for a simple Job with a `template` that starts one container.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The container in that Pod prints a message then pauses.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Modifying the pod template or switching to a new pod template has no direct effect on the Pods that already exist.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] If you change the pod template for a workload resource, that resource needs to create replacement Pods that use the updated template.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] For example, the StatefulSet controller ensures that the running Pods match the current pod template for each StatefulSet object.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] If you edit the StatefulSet to change its pod template, the StatefulSet starts to create new Pods based on the updated template.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Eventually, all of the old Pods are replaced with new Pods, and the update is complete.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Each workload resource implements its own rules for handling changes to the Pod template.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] If you want to read more about StatefulSet specifically, read Update strategy in the StatefulSet Basics tutorial.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] On Nodes, the kubelet does not directly observe or manage any of the details around pod templates and updates; those details are abstracted away.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] That abstraction and separation of concerns simplifies system semantics, and makes it feasible to extend the cluster's behavior without changing existing code.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] As mentioned in the previous section, when the Pod template for a workload resource is changed, the controller creates new Pods based on the updated template instead of updating or patching the existing Pods.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Kubernetes doesn't prevent you from managing Pods directly.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] It is possible to update some fields of a running Pod, in place.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] 2. updating the field from a positive number to a smaller, non-negative number.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The above update rules apply to regular pod updates, but other pod fields can be updated through *subresources*.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Different status fields may either be associated with the `metadata.generation` of the current sync loop, or with the `metadata.generation` of the previous sync loop.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The key distinction is whether a change in the `spec` is reflected directly in the `status` or is an indirect result of a running process.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] For status fields where the allocated spec is directly reflected, the `observedGeneration` will be associated with the current `metadata.generation` (Generation N).
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] For status fields that are an indirect result of running the spec, the `observedGeneration` will be associated with the `metadata.generation` of the previous sync loop (Generation N-1).
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Pods enable data sharing and communication among their constituent containers.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A Pod can specify a set of shared storage volumes.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] All containers in the Pod can access the shared volumes, allowing those containers to share data.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Volumes also allow persistent data in a Pod to survive in case one of the containers within needs to be restarted.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] See Storage for more information on how Kubernetes implements shared storage and makes it available to Pods.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Each Pod is assigned a unique IP address for each address family.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Every container in a Pod shares the network namespace, including the IP address and network ports.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Inside a Pod (and **only** then), the containers that belong to the Pod can communicate with one another using `localhost`.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] When containers in a Pod communicate with entities *outside the Pod*, they must coordinate how they use the shared network resources (such as ports).
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Within a Pod, containers share an IP address and port space, and can find each other via `localhost`.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The containers in a Pod can also communicate with each other using standard inter-process communications like SystemV semaphores or POSIX shared memory.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Containers in different Pods have distinct IP addresses and can not communicate by OS-level IPC without special configuration.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Containers that want to interact with a container running in a different Pod can use IP networking to communicate.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Containers within the Pod see the system hostname as being the same as the configured `name` for the Pod.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] There's more about this in the networking section.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] To set security constraints on Pods and containers, you use the `securityContext` field in the Pod specification.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] This field gives you granular control over what a Pod or individual containers can do.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] See Advanced Pod Configuration for more details.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] For basic security configuration, you should meet the Baseline Pod security standard and run containers as non-root.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] For advanced security context configuration including capabilities, seccomp profiles, and detailed security options, see the security concepts section.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] When you specify a Pod, you can optionally specify how much of each resource a container needs.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The most common resources to specify are CPU and memory (RAM).
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] When you specify the resource *request* for containers in a Pod, the kube-scheduler uses this information to decide which node to place the Pod on.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] When you specify a resource *limit* for a container, the kubelet enforces those limits so that the running container is not allowed to use more of that resource than the limit you set.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] CPU limits are enforced by CPU throttling.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] When a container approaches its CPU limit, the kernel restricts its access to CPU.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Memory limits are enforced by the kernel with out-of-memory (OOM) kills when a container exceeds its limit.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Setting CPU limits involves a trade-off.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] CPU limits help prevent noisy neighbor problems where a single workload starves others on the same node.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] This is especially important in multi-tenant environments.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] However, CPU limits can cause throttling even when the node has spare CPU capacity, potentially degrading latency-sensitive workload performance.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Whether to set CPU limits depends on your environment, workload characteristics, and isolation requirements.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] For details on resource units, enforcement behavior, and configuration examples, see Resource Management for Pods and Containers.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Static Pods are always bound to one Kubelet on a specific node.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The main use for static Pods is to run a self-hosted control plane: in other words, using the kubelet to supervise the individual control plane components.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Pods are designed to support multiple cooperating processes (as containers) that form a cohesive unit of service.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The containers in a Pod are automatically co-located and co-scheduled on the same physical or virtual machine in the cluster.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] The containers can share resources and dependencies, communicate with one another, and coordinate when and how they are terminated.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Some Pods have init containers as well as app containers.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] By default, init containers run and complete before the app containers are started.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] You can also have sidecar containers that provide auxiliary services to the main application Pod (for example: a service mesh).
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Enabled by default, the `SidecarContainers` feature gate allows you to specify `restartPolicy: Always` for init containers.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Setting the `Always` restart policy ensures that the containers where you set it are treated as *sidecars* that are kept running during the entire lifetime of the Pod.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] Containers that you explicitly define as sidecar containers start up before the main application Pod and remain running until the Pod is shut down.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] A *probe* is a diagnostic performed periodically by the kubelet on a container.
[src:kubernetes/workloads-pods] You can read more about probes in the Pod Lifecycle documentation.
